 Extract Coordinates from Image Metadata with ExifTool
Objectives
By the end of this lab, students will be able to:

Install and configure ExifTool on Linux systems
Extract GPS coordinates and metadata from digital images
Interpret EXIF data including latitude, longitude, and timestamps
Create automated scripts for batch GPS extraction
Visualize extracted coordinates using mapping tools
Apply geolocation techniques for OSINT investigations
Prerequisites
Before starting this lab, students should have:

Basic Linux command line proficiency
Understanding of GPS coordinate systems (latitude/longitude)
Familiarity with Python programming basics
Knowledge of file system navigation
Lab Environment
Al Nafi provides ready-to-use Linux-based cloud machines for this lab. Click Start Lab to access your pre-configured environment with all necessary tools.

Task 1: Install ExifTool and Setup Workspace
Step 1.1: Install ExifTool
Update your system and install ExifTool for metadata extraction:

# Update package repositories
sudo apt update

# Install ExifTool
sudo apt install exiftool -y

# Verify installation
exiftool -ver
Step 1.2: Create Lab Directory Structure
Organize your workspace for efficient data management:

# Create main lab directory
mkdir -p ~/gps_lab/{sample_images,extracted_data,scripts}
cd ~/gps_lab

# Verify structure
tree -L 1
